help_define('_HELP_IRECORDSTRUCTURE',       "=Record structures=\n\nA record may - but does not have to - consist of several areas overlapping with each other and these determine the structure.  \nFor example, a record of an address can contain one or more URL attributes.\n\nIf areas are intended to be used for a database, create them using the Combobox \"New...\" on the right hand side of the mask [[ieditrecords|edit records]].\n\nExisting areas can similarly be deleted, the symbol \"delete area\". In addition, the sequence of areas can be modified using the arrows.\n\nThe areas themselves are also filed in separate tables, which then also involve [[isecondarydata|secondary data]]");
help_define('_HELP_IREFERENCESOFRECORDS',   "=References and Links=\n\nReferences (and also \"inverted links\") mean references to a particular record in other records, ie. if records A, B and C each refer to D, record D has three references, A, B and C. This is also expressed as \"record D is referenced by A, B and C\".\n\nIt is therefore basically irrelevant whether A, B, C, and D appear as records in the same or in different tables. \n\nThe programme applies references to create links and for  \n[[iattributes|attributes]]. Internal references are also applied in [[isecondarydata|secondary data]] in the [[irecordstructure|record structure]] (areas in records).\n\nThe number of references in a record is displayed in mask [[ioverviewrecords|overview of records]]\nand mask [[ieditrecords|edit records]]\nand elsewhere. By clicking on this figure you enter a new mask showing all references individually.  \n\nServicing this mask is similar to the procedure described in \n[[ioverviewrecords|overview of records]],\nso please refer to that option for further information.");
