help_define('_HELP_USER8',                  "=User=\n\nFor general information, see [[ieditrecords|edit records]].\n\nNB: You can only administer users and rights if you have been given authorisation. Authorisation can be provided by the [[isupervisor|supervisor]].\n\nIn order to administer users, click on table \"user\" in the [[imainmenu|main menu / etc]].\n\nThis table contains a list of all users with access to the system. By clicking on a user you can modify his/her access rights in relation to every table and other areas of the system:\n\n- For '''rights on record level''', all users are organised first of all into '''Groups''', i.e. users belong to one or more groups (members of a group usually grant each other extensive rights to their records; the groups themselves are administered from another table, for which click on \"groups\" at the top left-hand side; the owner/originator can then determine to which group s/he wants to belong in relation to each of his/her records, and which rights s/he wants to retain or to give to other group members or users, see  [[ieditrecords|edit records]] under \"rights\").\n\n- The Supervisor issues '''rights on table level and/or field level''' (field \"rights\") independently of the groups. To do that, the table(s) and/or the field(s) for which a rule is required are selected by clicking on '''new grant...'''. For example, a click on \n\n-- '''my_table.*''' selects all fields in the table \"my_table\",\n\n-- '''*.my_field''' selects all fields \"my_fieldquot; in all tables containing it,\n\n-- '''*.*''' selects all fields and all tables including specials such as \"SUPERVISOR\" or \"LOCALIZE\".<br /><br />Rules can thus be constructed in relation to the rights '''new''', '''read''', '''edit''' and '''delete'''. The \"nearest\" rule will apply, i.e.:\"<br /><br />\n\n-- '''my_table.my_field''' supercedes \"my_table.*\", \"*.my_field\" and even \"*.*\"\n-- '''my_table.*''' supercedes the rule \"*.*\"in this table.\n-- '''*.my_field''' supercedes the rule \"*.*\" in this field.\n-- There is one exception to this principle: if, for example, there is a rule for '''*.my_field''' and '''my_table.*''', but not for '''my_table.my_field''', logic will prevail and the rights will be linked by AND.\n\n- A user with rights to write in the User table can '''create new users'''; however, s/he can only allocate groups and rights that s/he has him/herself, i.e. no user can create a user with more rights than s/he has him/herself.\n\n- A user who can modify '''SUPERVISOR.my_group''' is the supervisor for this group, which means that s/he can modify all records relating to this group, irrespective of whether this is allowed by the owner. However, ''which'' table or fields s/he can modify depends on the rights issued to him/her.\n\n- A user with rights to write in the Groups table can '''create new groups'''.\n\nYou can also set the name, the log-in name and the password for all users. However, the password may be altered independently by the user, see [[ipassword|change password]].\n\nUnder \"settings\" you will find the personlised [[isettings|settings]] applied by each user. If you add \n\"settings.editable=0\" to it, the user will be unable to alter the settings.  This can be useful for Guest Accounts or Multi-User Accounts.\n\nAt the bottom of the page, you will also find the time of the last successful log-in and the last failed log-in. After a number of failed log-ins, access by that user will be blocked for security reasons. This account can be released if you set \"number of login errors\" manually to zero. \n\n==Status code overview==\n\n| 0  | User has not logged in\n| 1  | User has logged in\n| >1 | Failed attempt to log in, user logged in successfully after an unspecified number of attempts, after a specified number of attempts user failed to log in.\n| >=1000 | Account blocked anyway. Set this number to zero to release.");
